# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: remote-sensing-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Once the parameters of the formula are stored, the image may be transformed dynamically at drawing time, or resampled to generate a georeferenced raster GIS file or orthophoto.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The term "georeferencing" has also been used to refer to other types of transformation from general expressions of geographic location (*geocodes*) to coordinate measurements, but most of these other methods are more commonly called geocoding.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Because of this ambiguity, *georegistration* is preferred by some to refer to the image transformation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Occasionally, this process has been called *rubbersheeting*, but that term is more commonly applied to a very similar process applied to vector GIS data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Compared to georeferencing, orthorectification accounts for the Earth's topography, sensor optical distortions, and sometimes other artifacts and is often preferred as a result.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] It is thus the extension of the typical task of curve fitting a relationship between two variables to four dimensions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Such that for every pixel in the image ( $x_{in},y_{in}$ being its column and row number, respectively), a corresponding real-world coordinate can be calculated.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Several types of functions are available in most GIS and remote sensing software for georeferencing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Where A-F are constant coefficients set for the entire image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] These formulas allow an image to be *moved* (the C and F coefficients specify the desired location of the top left corner of the image), *scaled* (without rotation, the A and E coefficients specify the size of each cell or spatial resolution), and *rotated*.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] In the last case, if the cell size is *r* in both the x and y directions, and the image is to be rotated *α* degrees counter-clockwise, then $A=E=r\cos(\alpha ),B=D=r\sin(\alpha )$ .
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The world file developed by Esri is a commonly used sidecar file that specifies these six coefficients for image georeferencing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Higher order polynomial transformations are also commonly used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The second-order terms (and third-order terms in a third-order polynomial) allow for the variable warping of the image, which is especially useful for removing the inherent distortion in aerial photographs.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] In addition to global parametric formulas, piecewise formulas can also be used, which transform different parts of the image in different ways.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] A common example is a Thin plate spline transformation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] It is very rare that a user would specify the parameters for the transformation directly.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Instead, most GIS and remote sensing software provides an interactive environment for visually aligning the image to the destination coordinate system.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The most common method for doing this is to create a series of *ground control points* (GCP).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] A ground control point is a location that can be identified on both the image and the ground, so that it has precise coordinates in both the image coordinate system ( $x_{in}$ = pixel column, $y_{in}$ = pixel row) and the ground coordinate system ( $x_{out},y_{out}$ ).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Easily visible locations that be precisely located are preferred as GCP's, such as a road intersection or the corner of a building.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] When very high accuracy registration is required, it is common to place or paint high-contrast markers on the ground at survey control monuments before the photography is taken, and use GNSS-measured coordinates for the output.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] In most software, these are entered by pointing at the location on the image, then pointing at the same location on a vector base map or orthophoto that is already in the desired coordinate system.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] This can then be moved and adjusted to improve accuracy.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] With a minimal set of GCPs, the known coordinates can be entered into the mathematical equations for the desired type of transformation, which can then be solved using linear algebra to determine the coefficients and derive the formulas to use for the entire grid.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] For example, the linear affine transformation above has six unknown coefficients, so six equations with known < $x_{in},y_{in},x_{out},y_{out}$ > are needed to derive them, which will require three ground control points.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The second-order polynomial requires a minimum of six ground control points, and so on.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The entered GCPs are rarely perfectly located and are even more rarely perfectly representative of the distortion in the rest of the image, but the algebraic solution, which appears to be a perfect match, masks any error.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] To avoid this, it is common to create many more than the minimal required set (creating an overdetermined system), and use least squares regression to derive a set of function parameters that most closely matches the points.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] This is almost never a perfect match, so the variance between each GCP location and the location predicted by the functions can be measured and summarized as a Root-mean-square error (RMSE).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] A lower RMSE thus means that the transformation formulas closely match the GCPs.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Once the function parameters are determined, the transformation functions can be used to transform every pixel of the image to its real-world location.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Two options are usually available for making this transformation permanent.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] One option is to save the parameters themselves as a form of metadata, either in the header of the image file itself (e.g., GeoTIFF), or in a sidecar file stored alongside the image file (e.g., a world file).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] With this metadata, the software can perform the transformation dynamically as it displays the image, so that it appears to align with other data in the desired coordinate system.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] The alternative method is rectification, in which the image is resampled to create a new raster grid that is natively tied to the coordinate system.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/georeferencing] Rectification was traditionally the only option, until the computing power became available for the intense calculations of dynamic coordinate transformations; even now, drawing and analysis performance is better with a rectified image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Whereas the human eye sees color of visible light in mostly three bands (long wavelengths, perceived as red; medium wavelengths, perceived as green; and short wavelengths, perceived as blue), spectral imaging divides the spectrum into many more bands.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] This technique of dividing images into bands can be extended beyond the visible.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In hyperspectral imaging, the recorded spectra have fine wavelength resolution and cover a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging measures continuous spectral bands, as opposed to multiband imaging which measures spaced spectral bands.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Engineers build hyperspectral sensors and processing systems for applications in astronomy, agriculture, molecular biology, biomedical imaging, geosciences, physics, and surveillance.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral sensors look at objects using a vast portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Certain objects leave unique "fingerprints" in the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Known as spectral signatures, these "fingerprints" enable identification of the materials that make up a scanned object.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] For example, a spectral signature for oil helps geologists find new oil fields.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Figuratively speaking, hyperspectral sensors collect information as a set of "images." Each image represents a narrow wavelength range of the electromagnetic spectrum, also known as a spectral band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] These "images" are combined to form a three-dimensional (*x*, *y*, *λ*) hyperspectral data cube for processing and analysis, where *x* and *y* represent two spatial dimensions of the scene, and *λ* represents the spectral dimension (comprising a range of wavelengths).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Technically speaking, there are four ways for sensors to sample the hyperspectral cube: spatial scanning, spectral scanning, snapshot imaging, and spatio-spectral scanning.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral cubes are generated from airborne sensors like NASA's *Airborne Visible/Infrared Imaging Spectrometer* (AVIRIS), or from satellites like NASA's EO-1 with its hyperspectral instrument Hyperion.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] However, for many development and validation studies, handheld sensors are used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The precision of these sensors is typically measured in spectral resolution, which is the width of each band of the spectrum that is captured.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] If the scanner detects a large number of fairly narrow frequency bands, it is possible to identify objects even if they are only captured in a handful of pixels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] However, spatial resolution is a factor in addition to spectral resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] If the pixels are too large, then multiple objects are captured in the same pixel and become difficult to identify.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] If the pixels are too small, then the intensity captured by each sensor cell is low, and the decreased signal-to-noise ratio reduces the reliability of measured features.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The acquisition and processing of hyperspectral images is also referred to as imaging spectroscopy or, with reference to the hyperspectral cube, as 3D spectroscopy.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] There are four basic techniques for acquiring the three-dimensional (*x*, *y*, *λ*) dataset of a hyperspectral cube.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The choice of technique depends on the specific application, seeing that each technique has context-dependent advantages and disadvantages.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In spatial scanning, each two-dimensional (2D) sensor output represents a full slit spectrum (*x*, *λ*).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging (HSI) devices for spatial scanning obtain slit spectra by projecting a strip of the scene onto a slit and dispersing the slit image with a prism or a grating.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] These systems have the drawback of having the image analyzed per lines (with a push broom scanner) and also having some mechanical parts integrated into the optical train.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] With these *line-scan cameras*, the spatial dimension is collected through platform movement or scanning.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] This requires stabilized mounts or accurate pointing information to 'reconstruct' the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Nonetheless, line-scan systems are particularly common in remote sensing, where it is sensible to use mobile platforms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Line-scan systems are also used to scan materials moving by on a conveyor belt.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] A special case of line scanning is *point scanning* (with a whisk broom scanner), where a point-like aperture is used instead of a slit, and the sensor is essentially one-dimensional instead of 2D.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In spectral scanning, each 2D sensor output represents a monochromatic (i.e. single wavelength), spatial (*x*, *y*)-map of the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI devices for spectral scanning are typically based on optical band-pass filters (either tunable or fixed).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The scene is spectrally scanned by exchanging one filter after another while the platform remains stationary.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In such "staring", wavelength scanning systems, spectral smearing can occur if there is movement within the scene, invalidating spectral correlation/detection.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Nonetheless, there is the advantage of being able to pick and choose spectral bands, and having a direct representation of the two spatial dimensions of the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] If the imaging system is used on a moving platform, such as an airplane, acquired images at different wavelengths corresponds to different areas of the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The spatial features on each of the images may be used to realign the pixels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In non-scanning, a single 2D sensor output contains all spatial (*x*, *y*) and spectral (*λ*) data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI devices for non-scanning yield the full datacube at once, without any scanning.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Figuratively speaking, a single snapshot represents a perspective projection of the datacube, from which its three-dimensional structure can be reconstructed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The most prominent benefits of these snapshot hyperspectral imaging systems are the *snapshot advantage* (higher light throughput) and shorter acquisition time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] However, computational effort and manufacturing costs are high.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In an effort to reduce the computational demands and potentially the high cost of non-scanning hyperspectral instrumentation, prototype devices based on Multivariate Optical Computing have been demonstrated.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] These devices have been based on the Multivariate Optical Element spectral calculation engine or the Spatial Light Modulator spectral calculation engine.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In these platforms, chemical information is calculated in the optical domain prior to imaging such that the chemical image relies on conventional camera systems with no further computing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] As a disadvantage of these systems, no spectral information is ever acquired, i.e. only the chemical information, such that post processing or reanalysis is not possible.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In spatiospectral scanning, each 2D sensor output represents a wavelength-coded ("rainbow-colored", *λ* = *λ*(*y*)), spatial (*x*, *y*)-map of the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] A prototype for this technique, introduced in 2014, consists of a camera at some *non-zero* distance behind a basic slit spectroscope (slit + dispersive element).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Advanced spatiospectral scanning systems can be obtained by placing a dispersive element before a spatial scanning system.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Scanning can be achieved by moving the whole system relative to the scene, by moving the camera alone, or by moving the slit alone.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Spatiospectral scanning unites some advantages of spatial and spectral scanning, thereby alleviating some of their disadvantages.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is part of a class of techniques commonly referred to as spectral imaging or spectral analysis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The term "hyperspectral imaging" derives from the development of NASA's Airborne Imaging Spectrometer (AIS) and AVIRIS in the mid-1980s.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Although NASA prefers the earlier term "imaging spectroscopy" over "hyperspectral imaging," use of the latter term has become more prevalent in scientific and non-scientific language.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In a peer reviewed letter, experts recommend using the terms "imaging spectroscopy" or "spectral imaging" and avoiding exaggerated prefixes such as "hyper-," "super-" and "ultra-," to prevent misnomers in discussion.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is related to multispectral imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The distinction between hyper- and multi-band is sometimes based incorrectly on an arbitrary "number of bands" or on the type of measurement.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging (HSI) uses continuous and contiguous ranges of wavelengths (e.g.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] 400 - 1100 nm in steps of 1 nm) whilst multiband imaging (MSI) uses a subset of targeted wavelengths at chosen locations (e.g.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Multiband imaging deals with several images at discrete and somewhat narrow bands.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Being "discrete and somewhat narrow" is what distinguishes multispectral imaging in the visible wavelength from color photography.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] A multispectral sensor may have many bands covering the spectrum from the visible to the longwave infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Multispectral images do not produce the "spectrum" of an object.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Landsat is a prominent practical example of multispectral imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral deals with imaging narrow spectral bands over a continuous spectral range, producing the spectra of all pixels in the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] A sensor with only 20 bands can also be hyperspectral when it covers the range from 500 to 700 nm with 20 bands each 10 nm wide, while a sensor with 20 discrete bands covering the visible, near, short wave, medium wave and long wave infrared would be considered multispectral.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In addition, some formal standards define HSI using a minimum number of spectral channels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] For example, the IEEE 4001 standard for hyperspectral data characterization defines hyperspectral imagery as containing 30 or more spectral bands, primarily for data interoperability, system classification, and metadata standardization.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral remote sensing is used in a wide array of applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] This technology is continually becoming more available to the public.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Organizations such as NASA and the USGS have catalogues of various minerals and their spectral signatures, and have posted them online to make them readily available for researchers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] On a smaller scale, NIR hyperspectral imaging can be used to rapidly monitor the application of pesticides to individual seeds for quality control of the optimum dose and homogeneous coverage.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Although the cost of acquiring hyperspectral images is typically high for specific crops and in specific climates, hyperspectral remote sensing use is increasing for monitoring the development and health of crops.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In Australia, work is under way to use imaging spectrometers to detect grape variety and develop an early warning system for disease outbreaks.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Furthermore, work is under way to use hyperspectral data to detect the chemical composition of plants, which can be used to detect the nutrient and water status of wheat in irrigated systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Another application in agriculture is the detection of animal proteins in compound feeds to avoid bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), also known as mad-cow disease.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Different studies have been done to propose alternative tools to the reference method of detection, (classical microscopy).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] One of the first alternatives is near infrared microscopy (NIR), which combines the advantages of microscopy and NIR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In 2004, the first study relating this problem with hyperspectral imaging was published.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral libraries that are representative of the diversity of ingredients usually present in the preparation of compound feeds were constructed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] These libraries can be used together with chemometric tools to investigate the limit of detection, specificity and reproducibility of the NIR hyperspectral imaging method for the detection and quantification of animal ingredients in feed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI cameras can also be used to detect stress from heavy metals in plants and become an earlier and faster alternative to post-harvest wet chemical methods.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is also used in zoology; it is used to investigate the spatial distribution of coloration and its extension into the near-infrared and SWIR range of the spectrum.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Some animals for example, such as some tropical frogs and certain leaf-sitting insects are highly reflective in the near-infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging can provide information about the chemical constituents of materials which makes it useful for waste sorting and recycling.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] It has been applied to distinguish between substances with different fabrics and to identify natural, animal and synthetic fibers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI cameras can be integrated with machine vision systems and, via simplifying platforms, allow end-customers to create new waste sorting applications and other sorting/identification applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] A system of machine learning and hyperspectral camera can distinguish between 12 different types of plastics such as PET and PP for automated separation of waste of, as of 2020, highly unstandardized plastics products and packaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Researchers at the Université de Montréal are working with Photon etc. and Optina Diagnostics to test the use of hyperspectral photography in the diagnosis of retinopathy and macular edema before damage to the eye occurs.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The metabolic hyperspectral camera will detect a drop in oxygen consumption in the retina, which indicates potential disease.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] An ophthalmologist will then be able to treat the retina with injections to prevent any potential damage.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In the food processing industry, hyperspectral imaging, combined with intelligent software, enables digital sorters (also called optical sorters) to identify and remove defects and foreign material (FM) that are invisible to traditional camera and laser sorters.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] By improving the accuracy of defect and FM removal, the food processor's objective is to enhance product quality and increase yields.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Adopting hyperspectral imaging on digital sorters achieves non-destructive, 100 percent inspection in-line at full production volumes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The sorter's software compares the hyperspectral images collected to user-defined accept/reject thresholds, and the ejection system automatically removes defects and foreign material.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Here, improved product quality, low false reject rates and the ability to handle high incoming defect loads often justify the cost of the technology.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Commercial adoption of hyperspectral sorters is also advancing at a fast pace in the potato processing industry where the technology promises to solve a number of outstanding product quality problems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Work is under way to use hyperspectral imaging to detect "sugar ends," "hollow heart" and "common scab," conditions that plague potato processors.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Geological samples, such as drill cores, can be rapidly mapped for nearly all minerals of commercial interest with hyperspectral imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Fusion of SWIR and LWIR spectral imaging is standard for the detection of minerals in the feldspar, silica, calcite, garnet, and olivine groups, as these minerals have their most distinctive and strongest spectral signature in the LWIR regions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral remote sensing of minerals is well developed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Many minerals can be identified from airborne images, and their relation to the presence of valuable minerals, such as gold and diamonds, is well understood.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Currently, progress is towards understanding the relationship between oil and gas leakages from pipelines and natural wells, and their effects on the vegetation and the spectral signatures.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Recent work includes the PhD dissertations of Werff and Noomen.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral surveillance is the implementation of hyperspectral scanning technology for surveillance purposes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is particularly useful in military surveillance because of countermeasures that military entities now take to avoid airborne surveillance.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The idea that drives hyperspectral surveillance is that hyperspectral scanning draws information from such a large portion of the light spectrum that any given object should have a unique spectral signature in at least a few of the many bands that are scanned.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has also shown potential to be used in facial recognition purposes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Facial recognition algorithms using hyperspectral imaging have been shown to perform better than algorithms using traditional imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Traditionally, commercially available thermal infrared hyperspectral imaging systems have needed liquid nitrogen or helium cooling, which has made them impractical for most surveillance applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In 2010, Specim introduced a thermal infrared hyperspectral camera that can be used for outdoor surveillance and UAV applications without an external light source such as the sun or the moon.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In astronomy, hyperspectral imaging is used to determine a spatially resolved spectral image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Since a spectrum is an important diagnostic, having a spectrum for each pixel allows more science cases to be addressed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] In astronomy, this technique is commonly referred to as integral field spectroscopy, and examples of this technique include FLAMES and SINFONI on the Very Large Telescope.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The Advanced CCD Imaging Spectrometer on the Chandra X-ray Observatory uses this technique.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Soldiers can be exposed to a wide variety of chemical hazards.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] These threats are mostly invisible but detectable by hyperspectral imaging technology.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The Telops Hyper-Cam, introduced in 2005, has demonstrated this at distances up to 5 km.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging in the visible near-infrared (VNIR) spectral range can effectively distinguish between dye-based and pigment-based inkjet prints, despite their similar appearance to the naked eye.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Research has demonstrated that these two ink types exhibit significantly different spectral characteristics, particularly in the near-infrared band (800-1000 nm), where dye-based inks show substantially higher reflectance compared to pigment-based inks.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] This difference is especially pronounced for black ink, where pigment-based ink maintains low reflectance across the entire VNIR spectrum while dye-based ink reflectance increases dramatically in the NIR range.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Thus, hyperspectral technology may offer practical applications in detecting print forgery, validating archival-quality prints, and potentially identifying specific printer types used to create documents.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Most countries require continuous monitoring of emissions produced by coal and oil-fired power plants, municipal and hazardous waste incinerators, cement plants, as well as many other types of industrial sources.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] This monitoring is usually performed using extractive sampling systems coupled with infrared spectroscopy techniques.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Some recent standoff measurements performed allowed the evaluation of the air quality but not many remote independent methods allow for low uncertainty measurements.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Recent research indicates that hyperspectral imaging may be useful to detect the development of cracks in pavements which are hard to detect from images taken with visible spectrum cameras.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has also been used to detect cancer, identify nerves and analyze bruises.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has recently been explored for use in autonomous driving and advanced driver-assistance systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] It can be used to improve pedestrian separability and object classification compared with conventional RGB cameras, and to help distinguish road conditions such as water or snow on the surface.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The primary advantage to hyperspectral imaging is that, because an entire spectrum is acquired at each point, the operator needs no prior knowledge of the sample, and postprocessing allows all available information from the dataset to be mined.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging can also take advantage of the spatial relationships among the different spectra in a neighbourhood, allowing more elaborate spectral-spatial models for a more accurate segmentation and classification of the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] The high cost and complexity of hyperspectral imaging equipment has limited its adoption, and analysis of hyperspectral data requires high computing power, especially for real-time or mobile applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Significant data storage and transmission capacities are necessary, since hyperspectral cubes are large, multidimensional datasets—for example, NASA's AVIRIS sensor, in use since 1987, produces about 500 megabytes per datacube.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Significant research has gone into onboard processing of hyperspectral data in satellites, to reduce transmission sizes by only sending detection results.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/hyperspectral-imaging] Increasingly, deep learning is being researched to lower the computational cost of processing hyperspectral data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging measures light in a small number (typically 3 to 15) of spectral bands.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] *Hyperspectral imaging* is a special case of spectral imaging where often hundreds of contiguous spectral bands are available.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] For different purposes, different combinations of spectral bands can be used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] They are usually represented with red, green, and blue channels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Mapping of bands to colors depends on the purpose of the image and the personal preferences of the analysts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Thermal infrared is often omitted from consideration due to poor spatial resolution, except for special purposes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] NIR is often shown as red, causing vegetation-covered areas to appear red.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Unlike other aerial photographic and satellite image interpretation work, these multispectral images do not make it easy to identify directly the feature type by visual inspection.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Hence the remote sensing data has to be classified first, followed by processing by various data enhancement techniques so as to help the user to understand the features that are present in the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Such classification is a complex task which involves rigorous validation of the training samples depending on the classification algorithm used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The techniques can be grouped mainly into two types.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Supervised classification makes use of training samples.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Training samples are areas on the ground for which there is ground truth, that is, what is there is known.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The spectral signatures of the training areas are used to search for similar signatures in the remaining pixels of the image, and we will classify accordingly.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] This use of training samples for classification is called supervised classification.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Expert knowledge is very important in this method since the selection of the training samples and a biased selection can badly affect the accuracy of classification.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Popular techniques include the maximum likelihood principle and convolutional neural network.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The maximum likelihood principle calculates the probability of a pixel belonging to a class (i.e. feature) and allots the pixel to its most probable class.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Newer convolutional neural network based methods account for both spatial proximity and entire spectra to determine the most likely class.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] In case of unsupervised classification no prior knowledge is required for classifying the features of the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The natural clustering or grouping of the pixel values (i.e. the gray levels of the pixels) are observed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Then a threshold is defined for adopting the number of classes in the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The finer the threshold value, the more classes there will be.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] However, beyond a certain limit the same class will be represented in different classes in the sense that variation in the class is represented.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] After forming the clusters, ground truth validation is done to identify the class the image pixel belongs to.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Thus in this unsupervised classification a priori information about the classes is not required.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] One of the popular methods in unsupervised classification is k-means clustering.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging measures light emission and is often used in detecting or tracking military targets.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] In 2003, researchers at the United States Army Research Laboratory and the Federal Laboratory Collaborative Technology Alliance reported a dual band multispectral imaging focal plane array (FPA).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] This FPA allowed researchers to look at two infrared (IR) planes at the same time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Because mid-wave infrared (MWIR) and long wave infrared (LWIR) technologies measure radiation inherent to the object and require no external light source, they also are referred to as thermal imaging methods.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The brightness of the image produced by a thermal imager depends on the objects emissivity and temperature.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Every material has an infrared signature that aids in the identification of the object.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] These signatures are less pronounced in hyperspectral systems (which image in many more bands than multispectral systems) and when exposed to wind and, more dramatically, to rain.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Sometimes the surface of the target may reflect infrared energy.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] This reflection may misconstrue the true reading of the objects' inherent radiation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Imaging systems that use MWIR technology function better with solar reflections on the target's surface and produce more definitive images of hot objects, such as engines, compared to LWIR technology.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] However, LWIR operates better in hazy environments like smoke or fog because less scattering occurs in the longer wavelengths.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Researchers claim that dual-band technologies combine these advantages to provide more information from an image, particularly in the realm of target tracking.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] For nighttime target detection, thermal imaging outperformed single-band multispectral imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Dual band MWIR and LWIR technology resulted in better visualization during the nighttime than MWIR alone.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The US Army reports that its dual band LWIR/MWIR FPA demonstrated better visualizing of tactical vehicles than MWIR alone after tracking them through both day and night.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] By analyzing the emissivity of ground surfaces, multispectral imaging can detect the presence of underground missiles.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Surface and sub-surface soil possess different physical and chemical properties that appear in spectral analysis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Disturbed soil has increased emissivity in the wavelength range of 8.5 to 9.5 micrometers while demonstrating no change in wavelengths greater than 10 micrometers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The US Army Research Laboratory's dual MWIR/LWIR FPA used "red" and "blue" detectors to search for areas with enhanced emissivity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The red detector acts as a backdrop, verifying realms of undisturbed soil areas, as it is sensitive to the 10.4 micrometer wavelength.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The blue detector is sensitive to wavelengths of 9.3 micrometers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] If the intensity of the blue image changes when scanning, that region is likely disturbed*.* The scientists reported that fusing these two images increased detection capabilities.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Intercepting an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) in its boost phase requires imaging of the hard body as well as the rocket plumes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] MWIR presents a strong signal from highly heated objects including rocket plumes, while LWIR produces emissions from the missile's body material.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The US Army Research Laboratory reported that with their dual-band MWIR/LWIR technology, tracking of the Atlas 5 Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicles, similar in design to ICBMs, picked up both the missile body and plumage.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Most radiometers for remote sensing (RS) acquire multispectral images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Dividing the spectrum into many bands, multispectral is the opposite of panchromatic, which records only the total intensity of radiation falling on each pixel.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Usually, Earth observation satellites have three or more radiometers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Each acquires one digital image (in remote sensing, called a 'scene') in a small spectral band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The bands are grouped into wavelength regions based on the origin of the light and the interests of the researchers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Modern weather satellites produce imagery in a variety of spectra.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] In the case of Landsat satellites, several different band designations have been used, with as many as 11 bands (Landsat 8) comprising a multispectral image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Spectral imaging with a higher radiometric resolution (involving hundreds or thousands of bands), finer spectral resolution (involving smaller bands), or wider spectral coverage may be called hyperspectral or ultraspectral.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging can be employed for investigation of paintings and other works of art.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The painting is irradiated by ultraviolet, visible and infrared rays and the reflected radiation is recorded in a camera sensitive in this region of the spectrum.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] The image can also be registered using the transmitted instead of reflected radiation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] In special cases the painting can be irradiated by UV, VIS or IR rays and the fluorescence of pigments or varnishes can be registered.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral analysis has assisted in the interpretation of ancient papyri, such as those found at Herculaneum, by imaging the fragments in the infrared range (1000 nm).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Often, the text on the documents appears to the naked eye as black ink on black paper.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] At 1000 nm, the difference in how paper and ink reflect infrared light makes the text clearly readable.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] It has also been used to image the Archimedes palimpsest by imaging the parchment leaves in bandwidths from 365–870 nm, and then using advanced digital image processing techniques to reveal the undertext with Archimedes' work.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging has been used in a Mellon Foundation project at Yale University to compare inks in medieval English manuscripts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging has also been used to examine discolorations and stains on old books and manuscripts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Comparing the "spectral fingerprint" of a stain to the characteristics of known chemical substances can make it possible to identify the stain.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] This technique has been used to examine medical and alchemical texts, seeking hints about the activities of early chemists and the possible chemical substances they may have used in their experiments.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/multispectral-imaging] Like a cook spilling flour or vinegar on a cookbook, an early chemist might have left tangible evidence on the pages of the ingredients used to make medicines.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The **normalized difference vegetation index** (**NDVI**) is a widely used metric for quantifying the health and density of vegetation using sensor data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It is calculated from spectrometric data at two specific bands: red and near-infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The spectrometric data is usually sourced from remote sensors, such as satellites.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The metric is popular in industry because of its accuracy.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It has a high correlation with the true state of vegetation on the ground.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The index is easy to interpret: NDVI will be a value between -1 and 1, where values close to zero will indicate little to no vegetation, negative values are associated with non-land surfaces or water, and higher values correspond to healthy, dense vegetation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It is used in applications such as agriculture, drought monitoring, and ecosystem analysis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The exploration of outer space started in earnest with the launch of Sputnik 1 by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This was the first man-made satellite orbiting the Earth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Subsequent successful launches, both in the Soviet Union (e.g., the Sputnik and Cosmos programs), and in the U.S.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] (e.g., the Explorer program), quickly led to the design and operation of dedicated meteorological satellites.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These are orbiting platforms embarking instruments specially designed to observe the Earth's atmosphere and surface with a view to improve weather forecasting.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Starting in 1960, the TIROS series of satellites embarked television cameras and radiometers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This was later (1964 onwards) followed by the Nimbus satellites and the family of Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer instruments on board the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) platforms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The latter measures the reflectance of the planet in red and near-infrared bands, as well as in the thermal infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In parallel, NASA developed the Earth Resources Technology Satellite (ERTS), which became the precursor to the Landsat program.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These early sensors had minimal spectral resolution, but tended to include bands in the red and near-infrared, which are useful to distinguish vegetation and clouds, amongst other targets.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With the launch of the first ERTS satellite – which was soon to be renamed Landsat 1 – on July 23, 1972 with its MultiSpectral Scanner (MSS) NASA funded a number of investigations to determine its capabilities for Earth remote sensing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] One of those early studies was directed toward examining the spring vegetation green-up and subsequent summer and fall dry-down (the so-called "vernal advancement and retrogradation") throughout the north to south expanse of the Great Plains region of the central U.S.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This region covered a wide range of latitudes from the southern tip of Texas to the U.S.-Canada border, which resulted in a wide range of solar zenith angles at the time of the satellite observations.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The researchers for this Great Plains study (PhD student Donald Deering and his advisor Dr.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Robert Hass) found that their ability to correlate, or quantify, the biophysical characteristics of the rangeland vegetation of this region from the satellite spectral signals was confounded by these differences in solar zenith angle across this strong latitudinal gradient.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With the assistance of a resident mathematician (Dr.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] John Schell), they studied solutions to this dilemma and subsequently developed the ratio of the difference of the red and infrared radiances over their sum as a means to adjust for or "normalize" the effects of the solar zenith angle.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The earliest reported use of NDVI in the Great Plains study was in 1973 by Rouse et al.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] John Rouse was the Director of the Remote Sensing Center of Texas A&M University where the Great Plains study was conducted).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] However, they were preceded in formulating a normalized difference spectral index by Kriegler et al. in 1969.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Soon after the launch of ERTS-1 (Landsat-1), Compton Tucker of NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center produced a series of early scientific journal articles describing uses of the NDVI.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Thus, NDVI was one of the most successful of many attempts to simply and quickly identify vegetated areas and their "condition," and it remains the most well-known and used index to detect live green plant canopies in multispectral remote sensing data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Once the feasibility to detect vegetation had been demonstrated, users tended to also use the NDVI to quantify the photosynthetic capacity of plant canopies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This, however, can be a rather more complex undertaking if not done properly, as is discussed below.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Live green plants absorb solar radiation in the photosynthetically active radiation (PAR) spectral region, which they use as a source of energy in the process of photosynthesis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Leaf cells have also evolved to re-emit solar radiation in the near-infrared spectral region (which carries approximately half of the total incoming solar energy), because the photon energy at wavelengths longer than about 700 nanometers is too low to synthesize organic molecules.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A strong absorption at these wavelengths would only result in overheating the plant and possibly damaging the tissues.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Hence, live green plants appear relatively dark in the PAR and relatively bright in the near-infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] By contrast, clouds and snow tend to be rather bright in the red (as well as other visible wavelengths) and quite dark in the near-infrared.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The pigment in plant leaves, chlorophyll, strongly absorbs visible light (from 400 to 700 nm) for use in photosynthesis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The cell structure of the leaves, on the other hand, strongly reflects near-infrared light (from 700 to 1100 nm).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The more leaves a plant has, the more these wavelengths of light are affected.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Since early instruments of Earth Observation, such as NASA's ERTS and NOAA's AVHRR, acquired data in visible and near-infrared, it was natural to exploit the strong differences in plant reflectance to determine their spatial distribution in these satellite images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] where Red and NIR stand for the spectral reflectance measurements acquired in the red (visible) and near-infrared regions, respectively.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These spectral reflectances are themselves ratios of the reflected radiation to the incoming radiation in each spectral band individually, hence they take on values between 0 and 1.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] By design, the NDVI itself thus varies between -1 and +1.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is functionally, but not linearly, equivalent to the simple infrared/red ratio (NIR/VIS).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The advantage of NDVI over a simple infrared/red ratio is therefore generally limited to any possible linearity of its functional relationship with vegetation properties (e.g. biomass).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The simple ratio (unlike NDVI) is always positive, which may have practical advantages, but it also has a mathematically infinite range (0 to infinity), which can be a practical disadvantage as compared to NDVI.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Also in this regard, note that the VIS term in the numerator of NDVI only scales the result, thereby creating negative values.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is functionally *and linearly* equivalent to the ratio NIR / (NIR+VIS), which ranges from 0 to 1 and is thus never negative nor limitless in range.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] But the most important concept in the understanding of the NDVI algebraic formula is that, despite its name, it is a transformation of a spectral ratio (NIR/VIS), and it has no functional relationship to a spectral difference (NIR-VIS).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In general, if there is much more reflected radiation in near-infrared wavelengths than in visible wavelengths, then the vegetation in that pixel is likely to be dense and may contain some type of forest.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Subsequent work has shown that the NDVI is directly related to the photosynthetic capacity and hence energy absorption of plant canopies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Although the index can take negative values, even in densely populated urban areas the NDVI usually has a (small) positive value.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Negative values are more likely to be observed in the atmosphere and some specific materials.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Within precision agriculture, NDVI data is used to assess crop health.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Today, this often involves agricultural drones, which are paired with NDVI to compare data and recognize crop health issues.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] One example of this is agriculture drones from PrecisionHawk and Sentera, which allow agriculturalists to capture and process NDVI data within one day, a change from the traditional NDVI uses and their long lag times.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In addition to drones, NDVI is used to monitor crop growth in stages over time, from early growth to maturity, helping to track how vegetation sprouts through its growing season.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This data collection helps detect spatial variability within field to check if some areas are growing healthier than others and if their timing is accurate for what stage they should be in.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] More specifically, farmers use NDVI to track things such as irrigation levels, application of fertilizer, and help reduce their waste and cost.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It can estimate leaf area index (LAI), biomass, vegetation cover, which farmers also need to determine crop yield.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This includes being able to identify plant stress much sooner than it can be seen.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This could include water stress, nutrient deficiencies, or diseases.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Since there is a prediction aspect to NDVI, it has been able to be used in yield prediction models since higher NDVI is more often linked to greater productivity/biomass.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Using a time-series, NDVI data gives farmers the opportunity to keep track of seasonal trends, compare those to that of previous years and brace for changes in upcoming climate variability that includes more drought or heatwaves.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] For example, NDVI can be used to monitor drought by tracking changes in vegetation green over time, where lower values can indicate plant stress due to reduced water availability.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This helps in analyzing large-scale ecosystem changes which includes seasonal vegetation cycles and long-term changes caused by climate change and land use change.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It also has applications in detecting deforestation and land cover damage since decreases in values often point to vegetation loss or degradation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This data is applied in urban studies to examine the relationship between surface temperature and vegetation cover, more useful in research on urban heat islands.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It can be seen from its mathematical definition that the NDVI of an area containing a dense vegetation canopy will tend to positive values (say 0.3 to 0.8) while clouds and snow fields will be characterized by negative values of this index.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The NDVI has been widely used in applications for which it was not originally designed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Using the NDVI for quantitative assessments (as opposed to qualitative surveys as indicated above) raises a number of issues that may seriously limit the actual usefulness of this index if they are not properly addressed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The following subsections review some of these issues.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is a very widely using system, however, it can become hard to interpret due to an oversimplification of more complex surface signals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Satellite data that is used includes a mixture of vegetation, soil, shadows, and the atmosphere itself, so it does not simply represent vegetation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Due to this oversimplification, information can be lost and in fact be misinterpreted of any actual vegetation conditions occurring at the time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Additionally, even if NDVI can cover larger areas, it's hard for it to capture individual plants which causes mismatches in field and satellite data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This makes linking productivity to an area much more uncertain for people like farmers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Differences between sensors and data processing methods can produce slightly different NDVI values making it hard for people to compare datasets from different timescales or platforms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This can also happen with the way people configure their sensor calibration or just how the resolution taken at the time was processed that could produce these changes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With this in mind, because of these limitation, NDVI can only be more reliably used for general vegetation pattern alongside other indices to provide a more accurate analysis and interpretation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A number of derivatives and alternatives to NDVI have been proposed in the scientific literature to address these limitations, including the Perpendicular Vegetation Index, the soil-adjusted vegetation index, the atmospherically resistant vegetation index and the global environment monitoring index.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Each of these attempted to include intrinsic correction(s) for one or more perturbing factors.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A current alternative adopted by USGS is the enhanced vegetation index (EVI), correcting for soil effects, canopy background, and aerosol influences.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In spite of many possible perturbing factors upon the NDVI, it remains a valuable quantitative vegetation monitoring tool when the photosynthetic capacity of the land surface needs to be studied at the appropriate spatial scale for various phenomena.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] Such band combinations are commonly bundled in satellite data sets, for example Landsat 7, which includes six 30 m resolution multispectral bands, a 60 m thermal infrared band plus a 15 m resolution panchromatic band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] SPOT, GeoEye and Maxar commercial data packages also commonly include both lower-resolution multispectral bands and a single panchromatic band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] One of the principal reasons for configuring satellite sensors this way is to keep satellite weight, cost, bandwidth and complexity down.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] Pan sharpening uses spatial information in the high-resolution grayscale band and color information in the multispectral bands to create a high-resolution color image, essentially increasing the resolution of the color information in the data set to match that of the panchromatic band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] Common color-space transformation used for pan sharpening are HSI (hue-saturation-intensity), and YCbCr.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] The same steps can also be performed using wavelet decomposition or PCA and replacing the first component with the pan band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] Pan-sharpening techniques can result in spectral distortions when pan sharpening satellite images as a result of the nature of the panchromatic band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] The Landsat panchromatic band for example is not sensitive to blue light.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] As a result, the spectral characteristics of the raw pansharpened color image may not exactly match those of the corresponding low-resolution RGB image, resulting in altered color tones.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/pansharpening] This has resulted in the development of many algorithms that attempt to reduce this spectral distortion and to produce visually pleasing images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In current usage, the term *remote sensing* generally refers to the use of satellite- or airborne-based sensor technologies to detect and classify objects on Earth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It includes the surface and the atmosphere and oceans, based on propagated signals (e.g. electromagnetic radiation).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It may be split into "active" remote sensing (when a signal is emitted by a sensor mounted on a satellite or aircraft to the object and its reflection is detected by the sensor) and "passive" remote sensing (when the reflection of sunlight is detected by the sensor).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing can be divided into two types of methods: *Passive remote sensing* and *active remote sensing.* Passive sensors gather radiation that is emitted or reflected by the object or surrounding areas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Reflected sunlight is the most common source of radiation measured by passive sensors.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Examples of passive remote sensors include film photography, infrared, charge-coupled devices, and radiometers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Active collection, on the other hand, emits energy in order to scan objects and areas whereupon a sensor then detects and measures the radiation that is reflected or backscattered from the target.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Radar and lidar are examples of active remote sensing where the time delay between emission and return is measured, establishing the location, speed and direction of an object.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing makes it possible to collect data of dangerous or inaccessible areas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing applications include monitoring deforestation in areas such as the Amazon Basin, glacial features in Arctic and Antarctic regions, and depth sounding of coastal and ocean depths.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Military collection during the Cold War made use of stand-off collection of data about dangerous border areas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing also replaces costly and slow data collection on the ground, ensuring in the process that areas or objects are not disturbed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The basis for multispectral collection and analysis is that of examined areas or objects that reflect or emit radiation that stand out from surrounding areas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] For a summary of major remote sensing satellite systems see the overview table.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Conventional radar is mostly associated with air traffic control, early warning, and certain large-scale meteorological data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Doppler radar is used by local law enforcements' monitoring of speed limits and in enhanced meteorological collection such as wind speed and direction within weather systems in addition to precipitation location and intensity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Other types of active collection includes plasmas in the ionosphere.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Interferometric synthetic aperture radar is used to produce precise digital elevation models of large scale terrain (See RADARSAT, TerraSAR-X, Magellan).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Laser and radar altimeters on satellites have provided a wide range of data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] By measuring the bulges of water caused by gravity, they map features on the seafloor to a resolution of a mile or so.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] By measuring the height and wavelength of ocean waves, the altimeters measure wind speeds and direction, and surface ocean currents and directions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Ultrasound (acoustic) and radar tide gauges are used to measure sea level, tides and wave direction in coastal and offshore tide gauges.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] LiDAR can be used to detect ground surface changes typically by creating Digital Surface Models (DSMs) or Digital Elevation Models (DEMs).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Vegetation remote sensing is a principal application of LIDAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The most common instruments in use are radiometers and photometers, which collect reflected and emitted radiation in a wide range of frequencies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The most prevalent of these frequencies are visible and infrared sensors, followed by microwave, gamma-ray, and rarely, ultraviolet.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] They may also be used to detect the emission spectra of various chemicals, providing data on chemical concentrations in the atmosphere.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Radiometers are also used at night, as artificial light emissions are a key signature of human activity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Applications include remote sensing of population, GDP, and damage to infrastructure from war or disasters.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Radiometers and radar onboard of satellites can be also used to monitor volcanic eruptions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Spectropolarimetric Imaging has been reported to be useful for target tracking purposes by researchers at the U.S.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] They determined that manmade items possess polarimetric signatures that are not found in natural objects.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] These conclusions were drawn from the imaging of military trucks, like the Humvee, and trailers with their acousto-optic tunable filter dual hyperspectral and spectropolarimetric VNIR Spectropolarimetric Imager.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Stereographic pairs of aerial photographs have often been used to make topographic maps by imagery and terrain analysts in trafficability and highway departments for potential routes, in addition to modelling terrestrial habitat features.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Simultaneous multi-spectral platforms such as Landsat have been in use since the early 1970s.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] These thematic mappers take images in multiple wavelengths and are usually found on Earth observation satellites, including (for example) the Landsat program or the IKONOS satellite.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Maps of land cover and land use from thematic mapping can be used to prospect for minerals, detect or monitor land usage, detect invasive vegetation, deforestation, and examine the health of indigenous plants and crops (satellite crop monitoring), including entire farming regions or forests.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Prominent scientists using remote sensing for this purpose include Janet Franklin and Ruth DeFries.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Landsat images are used by regulatory agencies such as KYDOW to indicate water quality parameters including Secchi depth, chlorophyll density, and total phosphorus content.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Weather satellites are used in meteorology and climatology.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Hyperspectral imaging produces image cubes where each pixel has full spectral information with imaging narrow spectral bands over a contiguous spectral range.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Hyperspectral imagers are used in various applications including mineralogy, biology, defence, and environmental measurements.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Within the scope of the combat against desertification, remote sensing allows researchers to follow up and monitor risk areas in the long term, to determine desertification factors, to support decision-makers in defining relevant measures of environmental management, and to assess their impacts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remotely sensed multi- and hyperspectral images can be used for assessing biodiversity at different spatial scales.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Since the spectral properties of different plants species are unique, it is possible to get information about properties that relates to biodiversity such as habitat heterogeneity, spectral diversity and plant functional trait.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing has also been used to detect rare plants to aid in conservation efforts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Prediction, detection, and the ability to record biophysical conditions were possible from medium to very high resolutions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Geodetic remote sensing can be gravimetric or geometric.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Overhead gravity data collection was first used in aerial submarine detection.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This data revealed minute perturbations in the Earth's gravitational field that may be used to determine changes in the mass distribution of the Earth, which in turn may be used for geophysical studies, as in GRACE.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Geometric remote sensing includes position and deformation imaging using InSAR, LIDAR, etc.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Seismograms taken at different locations can locate and measure earthquakes (after they occur) by comparing the relative intensity and precise timings.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Ultrasound acoustic sensing is made up of ultrasound sensors that emit high-frequency pulses and listening for echoes, used for detecting water waves and water level, as in tide gauges or for towing tanks.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] To coordinate a series of large-scale observations, most sensing systems depend on the following: platform location and the orientation of the sensor.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] High-end instruments now often use positional information from satellite navigation systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The rotation and orientation are often provided within a degree or two with electronic compasses.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Compasses can measure not just azimuth (i. e. degrees to magnetic north), but also altitude (degrees above the horizon), since the magnetic field curves into the Earth at different angles at different latitudes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] More exact orientations require gyroscopic-aided orientation, periodically realigned by different methods including navigation from stars or known benchmarks.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] There are applications of gamma rays to mineral exploration through remote sensing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In 1972 more than $2 million were spent on remote sensing applications with gamma rays to mineral exploration.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Gamma rays are used to search for deposits of uranium.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] By observing radioactivity from potassium, porphyry copper deposits can be located.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A high ratio of uranium to thorium has been found to be related to the presence of hydrothermal copper deposits.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Radiation patterns have also been known to occur above oil and gas fields, but some of these patterns were thought to be due to surface soils instead of oil and gas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The quality of remote sensing data consists of its spatial, spectral, radiometric and temporal resolutions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] – typically pixels may correspond to square areas ranging in side length from 1 to 1,000 metres (3.3 to 3,280.8 ft).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The bandwidth of the different frequency bands recorded – usually, this is related to the number of frequency bands recorded by the platform.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] spectrum, ranging from a spectral resolution of 0.7 to 2.1 μm.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The Hyperion sensor on Earth Observing-1 resolves 220 bands from 0.4 to 2.5 μm, with a spectral resolution of 0.10 to 0.11 μm per band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The number of different intensities of radiation the sensor is able to distinguish.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Typically, this ranges from 8 to 14 bits, corresponding to 256 levels of the gray scale and up to 16,384 intensities or "shades" of colour, in each band.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The frequency of flyovers by the satellite or plane, and is only relevant in time-series studies or those requiring an averaged or mosaic image as in deforesting monitoring.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This was first used by the intelligence community where repeated coverage revealed changes in infrastructure, the deployment of units or the modification/introduction of equipment.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Cloud cover over a given area or object makes it necessary to repeat the collection of said location.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In order to create sensor-based maps, most remote sensing systems expect to extrapolate sensor data in relation to a reference point including distances between known points on the ground.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This depends on the type of sensor used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] For example, in conventional photographs, distances are accurate in the center of the image, with the distortion of measurements increasing the farther you get from the center.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Another factor is that of the platen against which the film is pressed can cause severe errors when photographs are used to measure ground distances.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The step in which this problem is resolved is called georeferencing and involves computer-aided matching of points in the image (typically 30 or more points per image) which is extrapolated with the use of an established benchmark, "warping" the image to produce accurate spatial data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] As of the early 1990s, most satellite images are sold fully georeferenced.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In addition, images may need to be radiometrically and atmospherically corrected.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Allows avoidance of radiometric errors and distortions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The illumination of objects on the Earth's surface is uneven because of different properties of the relief.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This factor is taken into account in the method of radiometric distortion correction.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Radiometric correction gives a scale to the pixel values, e. g. the monochromatic scale of 0 to 255 will be converted to actual radiance values.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In rugged mountains, as a result of terrain, the effective illumination of pixels varies considerably.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In a remote sensing image, the pixel on the shady slope receives weak illumination and has a low radiance value, in contrast, the pixel on the sunny slope receives strong illumination and has a high radiance value.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] For the same object, the pixel radiance value on the shady slope will be different from that on the sunny slope.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Additionally, different objects may have similar radiance values.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] These ambiguities seriously affected remote sensing image information extraction accuracy in mountainous areas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It became the main obstacle to the further application of remote sensing images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The purpose of topographic correction is to eliminate this effect, recovering the true reflectivity or radiance of objects in horizontal conditions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Elimination of atmospheric haze by rescaling each frequency band so that its minimum value (usually realised in water bodies) corresponds to a pixel value of 0.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The digitizing of data also makes it possible to manipulate the data by changing gray-scale values.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Interpretation is the critical process of making sense of the data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Image Analysis is the recently developed automated computer-aided application that is in increasing use.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Object-Based Image Analysis (OBIA) is a sub-discipline of GI-Science devoted to partitioning remote sensing (RS) imagery into meaningful image-objects, and assessing their characteristics through spatial, spectral and temporal scale.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Old data from remote sensing is often valuable because it may provide the only long-term data for a large extent of geography.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] At the same time, the data is often complex to interpret, and bulky to store.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Modern systems tend to store the data digitally, often with lossless compression.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The difficulty with this approach is that the data is fragile, the format may be archaic, and the data may be easy to falsify.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] One of the best systems for archiving data series is as computer-generated machine-readable ultrafiche, usually in typefonts such as OCR-B, or as digitized half-tone images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Ultrafiches survive well in standard libraries, with lifetimes of several centuries.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] They can be created, copied, filed and retrieved by automated systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] They are about as compact as archival magnetic media, and yet can be read by human beings with minimal, standardized equipment.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The common analogy given to describe this is trying to determine the type of animal from its footprints.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] For example, while it is impossible to directly measure temperatures in the upper atmosphere, it is possible to measure the spectral emissions from a known chemical species (such as carbon dioxide) in that region.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The frequency of the emissions may then be related via thermodynamics to the temperature in that region.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A Level 1 data record is the most fundamental (i. e., highest reversible level) data record that has significant scientific utility, and is the foundation upon which all subsequent data sets are produced.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Level 2 is the first level that is directly usable for most scientific applications; its value is much greater than the lower levels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Level 2 data sets tend to be less voluminous than Level 1 data because they have been reduced temporally, spatially, or spectrally.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Level 3 data sets are generally smaller than lower level data sets and thus can be dealt with without incurring a great deal of data handling overhead.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] These data tend to be generally more useful for many applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The regular spatial and temporal organization of Level 3 datasets makes it feasible to readily combine data from different sources.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] While these processing levels are particularly suitable for typical satellite data processing pipelines, other data level vocabularies have been defined and may be appropriate for more heterogeneous workflows.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Satellite images provide very useful information to produce statistics on topics closely related to the territory, such as agriculture, forestry or land cover in general.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The first large project to apply Landsata 1 images for statistics was LACIE (Large Area Crop Inventory Experiment), run by NASA, NOAA and the USDA in 1974–77.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Many other application projects on crop area estimation have followed, including the Italian AGRIT project and the MARS project of the Joint Research Centre (JRC) of the European Commission.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It is relevant to highlight that probabilistic sampling is not critical for the selection of training pixels for image classification, but it is necessary for accuracy assessment of the classified images and area estimation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Additional care is recommended to ensure that training and validation datasets are not spatially correlated.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] We suppose now that we have classified images or a land cover map produced by visual photo-interpretation, with a legend of mapped classes that suits our purpose, taking again the example of wheat.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The straightforward approach is counting the number of pixels classified as wheat and multiplying by the area of each pixel.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The main strength of classified satellite images or other indicators computed on satellite images is providing cheap information on the whole target area or most of it.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This information usually has a good correlation with the target variable (ground truth) that is usually expensive to observe in an unbiased and accurate way.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Therefore, it can be observed on a probabilistic sample selected on an area sampling frame.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Traditional survey methodology provides different methods to combine accurate information on a sample with less accurate, but exhaustive, data for a covariable or proxy that is cheaper to collect.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] For agricultural statistics, field surveys are usually required, while photo-interpretation may better for land cover classes that can be reliably identified on aerial photographs or high resolution satellite images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Additional uncertainty can appear because of imperfect reference data (ground truth or similar).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] If we target other variables, such as crop yield or leaf area, we may need different indicators to be computed from images, such as the NDVI, a good proxy to chlorophyll activity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing of hydrologic processes can provide information on locations where *in situ* sensors may be unavailable or sparse.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It also enables observations over large spatial extents.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Many of the variables constituting the terrestrial water balance, for example surface water storage, soil moisture, precipitation, evapotranspiration, and snow and ice, are measurable using remote sensing at various spatial-temporal resolutions and accuracies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Sources of remote sensing include land-based sensors, airborne sensors and satellite sensors which can capture microwave, thermal and near-infrared data or use lidar, for example.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The modern discipline of remote sensing arose with the development of flight.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Tournachon (alias Nadar) made photographs of Paris from his balloon in 1858.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Messenger pigeons, kites, rockets and unmanned balloons were also used for early images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] With the exception of balloons, these first, individual images were not particularly useful for map making or for scientific purposes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Systematic aerial photography was developed for military surveillance and reconnaissance purposes beginning in World War I.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] After WWI, remote sensing technology was quickly adapted to civilian applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A more recent development is that of increasingly smaller sensor pods such as those used by law enforcement and the military, in both manned and unmanned platforms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The advantage of this approach is that this requires minimal modification to a given airframe.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Later imaging technologies would include infrared, conventional, Doppler and synthetic aperture radar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The development of artificial satellites in the latter half of the 20th century allowed remote sensing to progress to a global scale as of the end of the Cold War.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Instrumentation aboard various Earth observing and weather satellites such as Landsat, the Nimbus and more recent missions such as RADARSAT and UARS provided global measurements of various data for civil, research, and military purposes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Recent developments include, beginning in the 1960s and 1970s, the development of image processing of satellite imagery.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The use of the term "remote sensing" began in the early 1960s when Evelyn Pruitt realized that advances in science meant that aerial photography was no longer an adequate term to describe the data streams being generated by new technologies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] With assistance from her fellow staff member at the Office of Naval Research, Walter Bailey, she coined the term "remote sensing".
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Several research groups in Silicon Valley including NASA Ames Research Center, GTE, and ESL Inc. developed Fourier transform techniques leading to the first notable enhancement of imagery data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In 1999 the first commercial satellite (IKONOS) collecting very high resolution imagery was launched.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing has a growing relevance in the modern information society.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] It represents a key technology as part of the aerospace industry and bears increasing economic relevance – new sensors e.g.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] TerraSAR-X and RapidEye are developed constantly and the demand for skilled labour is increasing steadily.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Furthermore, remote sensing exceedingly influences everyday life, ranging from weather forecasts to reports on climate change or natural disasters.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] As an example, 80% of the German students use the services of Google Earth; in 2006 alone the software was downloaded 100 million times.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] But studies have shown that only a fraction of them know more about the data they are working with.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] There exists a huge knowledge gap between the application and the understanding of satellite images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing only plays a tangential role in schools, regardless of the political claims to strengthen the support for teaching on the subject.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A lot of the computer software explicitly developed for school lessons has not yet been implemented due to its complexity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Thereby, the subject is either not at all integrated into the curriculum or does not pass the step of an interpretation of analogue images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In fact, the subject of remote sensing requires a consolidation of physics and mathematics as well as competences in the fields of media and methods apart from the mere visual interpretation of satellite images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Many teachers have great interest in the subject "remote sensing", being motivated to integrate this topic into teaching, provided that the curriculum is considered.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In many cases, this encouragement fails because of confusing information.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In order to integrate remote sensing in a sustainable manner organizations like the EGU or Digital Earth encourage the development of learning modules and learning portals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Examples include: *FIS – Remote Sensing in School Lessons*, *Geospektiv*, *Ychange*, or Spatial Discovery, to promote media and method qualifications as well as independent learning.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Remote sensing data are processed and analyzed with computer software, known as a remote sensing application.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A large number of proprietary and open source applications exist to process remote sensing data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] An Earth observation satellite or Earth remote sensing satellite is a satellite used or designed for Earth observation (EO) from orbit, including spy satellites and similar ones intended for non-military uses such as environmental monitoring, meteorology, cartography and others.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The most common type are Earth imaging satellites, that take satellite images, analogous to aerial photographs; some EO satellites may perform remote sensing without forming pictures, such as in GNSS radio occultation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The first occurrence of satellite remote sensing can be dated to the launch of the first artificial satellite, Sputnik 1, by the Soviet Union on October 4, 1957.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Sputnik 1 sent back radio signals, which scientists used to study the ionosphere.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The United States Army Ballistic Missile Agency launched the first American satellite, Explorer 1, for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory on January 31, 1958.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The information sent back from its radiation detector led to the discovery of the Earth's Van Allen radiation belts.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The TIROS-1 spacecraft, launched on April 1, 1960, as part of NASA's Television Infrared Observation Satellite (TIROS) program, sent back the first television footage of weather patterns to be taken from space.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] In 2008, more than 150 Earth observation satellites were in orbit, recording data with both passive and active sensors and acquiring more than 10 terabits of data daily.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] By 2021, that total had grown to over 950, with the largest number of satellites operated by US-based company Planet Labs.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Most Earth observation satellites carry instruments that should be operated at a relatively low altitude.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Most orbit at altitudes above 500 to 600 kilometers (310 to 370 mi).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] Lower orbits have significant air-drag, which makes frequent orbit reboost maneuvers necessary.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The Earth observation satellites ERS-1, ERS-2 and Envisat of European Space Agency as well as the MetOp spacecraft of EUMETSAT are all operated at altitudes of about 800 km (500 mi).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The Proba-1, Proba-2 and SMOS spacecraft of European Space Agency are observing the Earth from an altitude of about 700 km (430 mi).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The Earth observation satellites of UAE, DubaiSat-1 & DubaiSat-2 are also placed in Low Earth orbits (LEO) orbits and providing satellite imagery of various parts of the Earth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] To get global coverage with a low orbit, a polar orbit is used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A low orbit will have an orbital period of about 100 minutes and the Earth will rotate around its polar axis about 25° between successive orbits.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] The ground track moves towards the west 25° each orbit, allowing a different section of the globe to be scanned with each orbit.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] A geostationary orbit, at 36,000 km (22,000 mi), allows a satellite to hover over a constant spot on the earth since the orbital period at this altitude is 24 hours.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This allows uninterrupted coverage of more than 1/3 of the Earth per satellite, so three satellites, spaced 120° apart, can cover the whole Earth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/remote-sensing] This type of orbit is mainly used for meteorological satellites.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] To create a SAR image, successive pulses of radio waves are transmitted to "illuminate" a target scene, and the echo of each pulse is received and recorded.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The pulses are transmitted and the echoes received using a single beam-forming antenna, with wavelengths of a meter down to several millimeters.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As the SAR device on board the aircraft or spacecraft moves, the antenna location relative to the target changes with time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Signal processing of the successive recorded radar echoes allows the combining of the recordings from these multiple antenna positions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This process forms the *synthetic antenna aperture* and allows the creation of higher-resolution images than would otherwise be possible with a given physical antenna.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR is capable of high-resolution remote sensing, independent of flight altitude, and independent of weather, as SAR can select frequencies to avoid weather-caused signal attenuation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR has day and night imaging capability as illumination is provided by the SAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR images have wide applications in remote sensing and mapping of surfaces of the Earth and other planets.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Examples include topography, oceanography, glaciology, geology (for example, terrain discrimination and subsurface imaging).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can also be used in forestry to determine forest height, biomass, and deforestation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Volcano and earthquake monitoring use differential interferometry.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can also be applied for monitoring civil infrastructure stability such as bridges.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR is useful in environment monitoring such as oil spills, flooding, urban growth, and military surveillance: including strategic policy and tactical assessment.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR can be implemented as inverse SAR by observing a moving target over a substantial time with a stationary antenna.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A *synthetic-aperture radar* is an imaging radar mounted on a moving platform.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is based on the fact that "radar reflections from discrete objects in a passing radar beam field each [have] a minute Doppler, or speed, shift relative to the antenna".
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In order to realise this concept, electromagnetic waves are transmitted sequentially, the echoes are collected and the system electronics digitizes and stores the data for subsequent processing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As transmission and reception occur at different times, they map to different small positions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The well ordered combination of the received signals builds a virtual aperture that is much longer than the physical antenna width.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] That is the source of the term "synthetic aperture," giving it the property of an imaging radar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The range direction is perpendicular to the flight track and perpendicular to the azimuth direction, which is also known as the *along-track* direction because it is in line with the position of the object within the antenna's field of view.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The 3D processing is done in two stages.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The azimuth and range direction are focused for the generation of 2D (azimuth-range) high-resolution images, after which a digital elevation model (DEM) is used to measure the phase differences between complex images, which is determined from different look angles to recover the height information.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This height information, along with the azimuth-range coordinates provided by 2-D SAR focusing, gives the third dimension, which is the elevation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The first step requires only standard processing algorithms, for the second step, additional pre-processing such as image co-registration and phase calibration is used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In addition, multiple baselines can be used to extend 3D imaging to the *time dimension*.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] 4D and multi-D SAR imaging allows imaging of complex scenarios, such as urban areas, and has improved performance with respect to classical interferometric techniques such as persistent scatterer interferometry (PSI).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR algorithms model the scene as a set of point targets that do not interact with each other (the Born approximation).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] While the details of various SAR algorithms differ, SAR processing in each case is the application of a matched filter to the raw data, for each pixel in the output image, where the matched filter coefficients are the response from a single isolated point target.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In the early days of SAR processing, the raw data was recorded on film and the postprocessing by matched filter was implemented optically using lenses of conical, cylindrical and spherical shape.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The Range-Doppler algorithm is an example of a more recent approach.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Synthetic-aperture radar determines the 3D reflectivity from measured SAR data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is basically a spectrum estimation, because for a specific cell of an image, the complex-value SAR measurements of the SAR image stack are a sampled version of the Fourier transform of reflectivity in elevation direction, but the Fourier transform is irregular.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus the spectral estimation techniques are used to improve the resolution and reduce speckle compared to the results of conventional Fourier transform SAR imaging techniques.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] FFT (Fast Fourier Transform i.e., periodogram or matched filter) is one such method, which is used in the majority of the spectral estimation algorithms, and there are many fast algorithms for computing the multidimensional discrete Fourier transform.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Computational *Kronecker-core array algebra* is a popular algorithm used as new variant of FFT algorithms for the processing in multidimensional synthetic-aperture radar (SAR) systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This algorithm uses a study of theoretical properties of input/output data indexing sets and groups of permutations.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A branch of finite multi-dimensional linear algebra is used to identify similarities and differences among various FFT algorithm variants and to create new variants.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Each multidimensional DFT computation is expressed in matrix form.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The multidimensional DFT matrix, in turn, is disintegrated into a set of factors, called functional primitives, which are individually identified with an underlying software/hardware computational design.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The FFT implementation is essentially a realization of the mapping of the mathematical framework through generation of the variants and executing matrix operations.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The performance of this implementation may vary from machine to machine, and the objective is to identify on which machine it performs best.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The Capon spectral method, also called the minimum-variance method, is a multidimensional array-processing technique.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Therefore, it passes a 2D sinusoid at a given frequency without distortion while minimizing the variance of the noise of the resulting image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The purpose is to compute the spectral estimate efficiently.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where *R* is the covariance matrix, and $a_{\omega _{1},\omega _{2}}^{*}$ is the 2D complex-conjugate transpose of the Fourier vector.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The computation of this equation over all frequencies is time-consuming.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is seen that the forward–backward Capon estimator yields better estimation than the forward-only classical Capon approach.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The main reason behind this is that while the forward–backward Capon uses both the forward and backward data vectors to obtain the estimate of the covariance matrix, the forward-only Capon uses only the forward data vectors to estimate the covariance matrix.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The APES (amplitude and phase estimation) method is also a matched-filter-bank method, which assumes that the phase history data is a sum of 2D sinusoids in noise.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Obtaining the spectrum estimate for $\omega \in [0,2\pi )$ from the filtered data.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Empirically, the APES method results in wider spectral peaks than the Capon method, but more accurate spectral estimates for amplitude in SAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In the Capon method, although the spectral peaks are narrower than the APES, the sidelobes are higher than that for the APES.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] As a result, the estimate for the amplitude is expected to be less accurate for the Capon method than for the APES method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The APES method requires about 1.5 times more computation than the Capon method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAMV method is a parameter-free sparse signal reconstruction based algorithm.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It achieves super-resolution and is robust to highly correlated signals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The name emphasizes its basis on the asymptotically minimum variance (AMV) criterion.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is a powerful tool for the recovery of both the amplitude and frequency characteristics of multiple highly correlated sources in challenging environment (e.g., limited number of snapshots, low signal-to-noise ratio).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Applications include synthetic-aperture radar imaging and various source localization.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAMV method is capable of achieving resolution higher than some established parametric methods, e.g., MUSIC, especially with highly correlated signals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Computational complexity of the SAMV method is higher due to its iterative procedure.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This subspace decomposition method separates the eigenvectors of the autocovariance matrix into those corresponding to signals and to clutter.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where ⊗ denotes the Kronecker product of the two vectors.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] MUSIC detects frequencies in a signal by performing an eigen decomposition on the covariance matrix of a data vector of the samples obtained from the samples of the received signal.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] When all of the eigenvectors are included in the clutter subspace (model order = 0) the EV method becomes identical to the Capon method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus the determination of model order is critical to operation of the EV method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The eigenvalue of the R matrix decides whether its corresponding eigenvector corresponds to the clutter or to the signal subspace.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The MUSIC method is considered to be a poor performer in SAR applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This method uses a constant instead of the clutter subspace.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In this method, the denominator is equated to zero when a sinusoidal signal corresponding to a point in the SAR image is in alignment to one of the signal subspace eigenvectors which is the peak in image estimate.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Thus this method does not accurately represent the scattering intensity at each point, but show the particular points of the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Backprojection Algorithm has two methods: *Time-domain Backprojection* and *Frequency-domain Backprojection*.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The time-domain Backprojection has more advantages over frequency-domain and thus, is more preferred.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The time-domain Backprojection forms images or spectrums by matching the data acquired from the radar and as per what it expects to receive.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It can be considered as an ideal matched-filter for synthetic-aperture radar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There is no need of having a different motion compensation step due to its quality of handling non-ideal motion/sampling.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It can also be used for various imaging geometries.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In GEO-SAR, to focus specially on the relative moving track, the backprojection algorithm works very well.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It uses the concept of Azimuth Processing in the time domain.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For the satellite-ground geometry, GEO-SAR plays a significant role.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The procedure of this concept is elaborated as follows.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The range of the data is then compressed, using the concept of "Matched Filtering" for every segment/sub-aperture created.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is given by- ${\textstyle s(t,\tau )=\exp \left(-j\cdot {\frac {4\pi }{\lambda }}\cdot R(t)\right)\cdot \operatorname {sinc} \left(\tau -{\frac {2}{c}}\cdot R(t)\right)}$ where *τ* is the range time, *t* is the azimuthal time, *λ* is the wavelength, *c* is the speed of light.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Accuracy in the "Range Migration Curve" is achieved by range interpolation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The pixel locations of the ground in the image is dependent on the satellite–ground geometry model.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Grid-division is now done as per the azimuth time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Calculations for the "slant range" (range between the antenna's phase center and the point on the ground) are done for every azimuth time using coordinate transformations.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Azimuth Compression is done after the previous step.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Step 5 and 6 are repeated for every pixel, to cover every pixel, and conduct the procedure on every sub-aperture.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Lastly, all the sub-apertures of the image created throughout, are superimposed onto each other and the ultimate HD image is generated.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Capon and APES can yield more accurate spectral estimates with much lower sidelobes and more narrow spectral peaks than the fast Fourier transform (FFT) method, which is also a special case of the FIR filtering approaches.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is seen that although the APES algorithm gives slightly wider spectral peaks than the Capon method, the former yields more accurate overall spectral estimates than the latter and the FFT method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] FFT method is fast and simple but have larger sidelobes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Capon has high resolution but high computational complexity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] EV also has high resolution and high computational complexity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] APES has higher resolution, faster than capon and EV but high computational complexity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] MUSIC method is not generally suitable for SAR imaging, as whitening the clutter eigenvalues destroys the spatial inhomogeneities associated with terrain clutter or other diffuse scattering in SAR imagery.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] But it offers higher frequency resolution in the resulting power spectral density (PSD) than the fast Fourier transform (FFT)-based methods.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The backprojection algorithm is computationally expensive.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It is specifically attractive for sensors that are wideband, wide-angle, and/or have long coherent apertures with substantial off-track motion.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR requires that echo captures be taken at multiple antenna positions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The more captures taken (at different antenna locations) the more reliable the target characterization.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Multiple captures can be obtained by moving a single antenna to different locations, by placing multiple stationary antennas at different locations, or combinations thereof.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The advantage of a single moving antenna is that it can be easily placed in any number of positions to provide any number of monostatic waveforms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For example, an antenna mounted on an airplane takes many captures per second as the plane travels.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The principal advantages of multiple static antennas are that a moving target can be characterized (assuming the capture electronics are fast enough), that no vehicle or motion machinery is necessary, and that antenna positions need not be derived from other, sometimes unreliable, information.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] (One problem with SAR aboard an airplane is knowing precise antenna positions as the plane travels).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For multiple static antennas, all combinations of monostatic and multistatic radar waveform captures are possible.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Note, however, that it is not advantageous to capture a waveform for each of both transmission directions for a given pair of antennas, because those waveforms will be identical.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where *N* is the number of unique antenna positions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It may be orthogonal to the flight path, or it may be squinted slightly forward or backward.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] When the antenna aperture travels along the flight path, a signal is transmitted at a rate equal to the pulse repetition frequency (PRF).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The lower boundary of the PRF is determined by the Doppler bandwidth of the radar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The backscatter of each of these signals is commutatively added on a pixel-by-pixel basis to attain the fine azimuth resolution desired in radar imagery.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where $\Delta \theta _{a}$ is the angle formed between the beginning and end of the imaging, as shown in the diagram of spotlight imaging and $r_{0}$ is the range distance.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The spotlight mode gives better resolution albeit for a smaller ground patch.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In this mode, the illuminating radar beam is steered continually as the aircraft moves, so that it illuminates the same patch over a longer period of time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This mode is not a traditional continuous-strip imaging mode; however, it has high azimuth resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A technical explanation of spotlight SAR from first principles is offered in.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] While operating as a scan mode SAR, the antenna beam sweeps periodically and thus cover much larger area than the spotlight and stripmap modes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] However, the azimuth resolution become much lower than the stripmap mode due to the decreased azimuth bandwidth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Clearly there is a balance achieved between the azimuth resolution and the scan area of SAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Here, the synthetic aperture is shared between the sub swaths, and it is not in direct contact within one subswath.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Mosaic operation is required in azimuth and range directions to join the azimuth bursts and the range sub-swaths.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Different materials reflect radar waves with different intensities, but anisotropic materials such as grass often reflect different polarizations with different intensities.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Some materials will also convert one polarization into another.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] By emitting a mixture of polarizations and using receiving antennas with a specific polarization, several images can be collected from the same series of pulses.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Frequently three such RX-TX polarizations (HH-pol, VV-pol, VH-pol) are used as the three color channels in a synthesized image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This is what has been done in the picture at right.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Interpretation of the resulting colors requires significant testing of known materials.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] New developments in polarimetry include using the changes in the random polarization returns of some surfaces (such as grass or sand) and between two images of the same location at different times to determine where changes not visible to optical systems occurred.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Examples include subterranean tunneling or paths of vehicles driving through the area being imaged.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Enhanced SAR sea oil slick observation has been developed by appropriate physical modelling and use of fully polarimetric and dual-polarimetric measurements.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR polarimetry is a technique used for deriving qualitative and quantitative physical information for land, snow and ice, ocean and urban applications based on the measurement and exploration of the polarimetric properties of man-made and natural scatterers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] *Terrain* and *land use* classification is one of the most important applications of polarimetric synthetic-aperture radar (PolSAR).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR polarimetry uses a scattering matrix (S) to identify the scattering behavior of objects after an interaction with electromagnetic wave.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The matrix is represented by a combination of horizontal and vertical polarization states of transmitted and received signals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] where, HH is for horizontal transmit and horizontal receive, VV is for vertical transmit and vertical receive, HV is for horizontal transmit and vertical receive, and VH for vertical transmit and horizontal receive.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The first two of these polarization combinations are referred to as like-polarized (or co-polarized), because the transmit and receive polarizations are the same.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The last two combinations are referred to as cross-polarized because the transmit and receive polarizations are orthogonal to one another.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The three-component scattering power model by Freeman and Durden is successfully used for the decomposition of a PolSAR image, applying the reflection symmetry condition using covariance matrix.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The method is based on simple physical scattering mechanisms (surface scattering, double-bounce scattering, and volume scattering).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The advantage of this scattering model is that it is simple and easy to implement for image processing.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There are 2 major approaches for a 3 $\times$ 3 polarimetric matrix decomposition.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] One is the lexicographic covariance matrix approach based on physically measurable parameters, and the other is the Pauli decomposition which is a coherent decomposition matrix.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It represents all the polarimetric information in a single SAR image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The polarimetric information of [S] could be represented by the combination of the intensities $|S_{HH}|^{2},|S_{VV}|^{2},2|S_{HV}|^{2}$ in a single RGB image where all the previous intensities will be coded as a color channel.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For PolSAR image analysis, there can be cases where reflection symmetry condition does not hold.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In those cases a *four-component scattering model* can be used to decompose polarimetric synthetic-aperture radar (SAR) images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This approach deals with the non-reflection symmetric scattering case.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It includes and extends the three-component decomposition method introduced by Freeman and Durden to a fourth component by adding the helix scattering power.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This helix power term generally appears in complex urban area but disappears for a natural distributed scatterer.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There is also an improved method using the four-component decomposition algorithm, which was introduced for the general polSAR data image analyses.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The SAR data is first filtered which is known as speckle reduction, then each pixel is decomposed by four-component model to determine the surface scattering power ( $P_{s}$ ), double-bounce scattering power ( $P_{d}$ ), volume scattering power ( $P_{v}$ ), and helix scattering power ( $P_{c}$ ).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The pixels are then divided into 5 classes (surface, double-bounce, volume, helix, and mixed pixels) classified with respect to maximum powers.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A mixed category is added for the pixels having two or three equal dominant scattering powers after computation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The process continues as the pixels in all these categories are divided in 20 small clutter approximately of same number of pixels and merged as desirable, this is called cluster merging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] They are iteratively classified and then automatically color is delivered to each class.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The summarization of this algorithm leads to an understanding that, brown colors denotes the surface scattering classes, red colors for double-bounce scattering classes, green colors for volume scattering classes, and blue colors for helix scattering classes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Although this method is aimed for non-reflection case, it automatically includes the reflection symmetry condition, therefore in can be used as a general case.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It also preserves the scattering characteristics by taking the mixed scattering category into account therefore proving to be a better algorithm.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Rather than discarding the phase data, information can be extracted from it.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] If two observations of the same terrain from very similar positions are available, aperture synthesis can be performed to provide the resolution performance which would be given by a radar system with dimensions equal to the separation of the two measurements.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This technique is called interferometric SAR or InSAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] If the two samples are obtained simultaneously (perhaps by placing two antennas on the same aircraft, some distance apart), then any phase difference will contain information about the angle from which the radar echo returned.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Combining this with the distance information, one can determine the position in three dimensions of the image pixel.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In other words, one can extract terrain altitude as well as radar reflectivity, producing a digital elevation model (DEM) with a single airplane pass.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] One aircraft application at the Canada Centre for Remote Sensing produced digital elevation maps with a resolution of 5 m and altitude errors also about 5 m.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Interferometry was used to map many regions of the Earth's surface with unprecedented accuracy using data from the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] If the two samples are separated in time, perhaps from two flights over the same terrain, then there are two possible sources of phase shift.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The first is terrain altitude, as discussed above.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The second is terrain motion: if the terrain has shifted between observations, it will return a different phase.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The amount of shift required to cause a significant phase difference is on the order of the wavelength used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This means that if the terrain shifts by centimeters, it can be seen in the resulting image (a digital elevation map must be available to separate the two kinds of phase difference; a third pass may be necessary to produce one).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This second method offers a powerful tool in geology and geography.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Glacier flow can be mapped with two passes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Maps showing the land deformation after a minor earthquake or after a volcanic eruption (showing the shrinkage of the whole volcano by several centimeters) have been published.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Differential interferometry (D-InSAR) requires taking at least two images with addition of a DEM.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The DEM can be either produced by GPS measurements or could be generated by interferometry as long as the time between acquisition of the image pairs is short, which guarantees minimal distortion of the image of the target surface.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In principle, 3 images of the ground area with similar image acquisition geometry is often adequate for D-InSar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The principle for detecting ground movement is quite simple.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] One interferogram is created from the first two images; this is also called the reference interferogram or topographical interferogram.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A second interferogram is created that captures topography + distortion.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Subtracting the latter from the reference interferogram can reveal differential fringes, indicating movement.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The described 3 image D-InSAR generation technique is called 3-pass or double-difference method.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Differential fringes which remain as fringes in the differential interferogram are a result of SAR range changes of any displaced point on the ground from one interferogram to the next.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In the differential interferogram, each fringe is directly proportional to the SAR wavelength, which is about 5.6 cm for ERS and RADARSAT single phase cycle.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Surface displacement away from the satellite look direction causes an increase in path (translating to phase) difference.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Since the signal travels from the SAR antenna to the target and back again, the measured displacement is twice the unit of wavelength.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This means in differential interferometry one fringe cycle −π to +π or one wavelength corresponds to a displacement relative to SAR antenna of only half wavelength (2.8 cm).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] There are various publications on measuring subsidence movement, slope stability analysis, landslide, glacier movement, etc. tooling D-InSAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Further advancement to this technique whereby differential interferometry from satellite SAR ascending pass and descending pass can be used to estimate 3-D ground movement.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Research in this area has shown accurate measurements of 3-D ground movement with accuracies comparable to GPS based measurements can be achieved.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] SAR Tomography is a subfield of a concept named as multi-baseline interferometry.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It has been developed to give a 3D exposure to the imaging, which uses the beam formation concept.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] It can be used when the use demands a focused phase concern between the magnitude and the phase components of the SAR data, during information retrieval.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] One of the major advantages of Tomo-SAR is that it can separate out the parameters which get scattered, irrespective of how different their motions are.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] On using Tomo-SAR with differential interferometry, a new combination named "differential tomography" (Diff-Tomo) is developed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Tomo-SAR has an application based on radar imaging, which is the depiction of Ice Volume and Forest Temporal Coherence (**Temporal coherence** describes the correlation between waves observed at different moments in time).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Conventional radar systems emit bursts of radio energy with a fairly narrow range of frequencies.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A narrow-band channel, by definition, does not allow rapid changes in modulation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Ultra-wideband (UWB) refers to any radio transmission that uses a very large bandwidth – which is the same as saying it uses very rapid changes in modulation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Although there is no set bandwidth value that qualifies a signal as "UWB", systems using bandwidths greater than a sizable portion of the center frequency (typically about ten percent, or so) are most often called "UWB" systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A typical UWB system might use a bandwidth of one-third to one-half of its center frequency.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] For example, some systems use a bandwidth of about 1 GHz centered around 3 GHz.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The two most common methods to increase signal bandwidth used in UWB radar, including SAR, are very short pulses and high-bandwidth chirping.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A general description of chirping appears elsewhere in this article.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The bandwidth of a chirped system can be as narrow or as wide as the designers desire.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Pulse-based UWB systems, being the more common method associated with the term "UWB radar", are described here.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A pulse-based radar system transmits very short pulses of electromagnetic energy, typically only a few waves or less.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A very short pulse is, of course, a very rapidly changing signal, and thus occupies a very wide bandwidth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This allows far more accurate measurement of distance, and thus resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The main disadvantage of pulse-based UWB SAR is that the transmitting and receiving front-end electronics are difficult to design for high-power applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Specifically, the transmit duty cycle is so exceptionally low and pulse time so exceptionally short, that the electronics must be capable of extremely high instantaneous power to rival the average power of conventional radars.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] However, this limitation is solved in chirped UWB radar systems.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The principal advantages of UWB radar are better resolution (a few millimeters using commercial off-the-shelf electronics) and more spectral information of target reflectivity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Doppler Beam Sharpening commonly refers to the method of processing unfocused real-beam phase history to achieve better resolution than could be achieved by processing the real beam without it.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Because the real aperture of the radar antenna is so small (compared to the wavelength in use), the radar energy spreads over a wide area (usually many degrees wide in a direction orthogonal (at right angles) to the direction of the platform (aircraft)).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Doppler-beam sharpening takes advantage of the motion of the platform in that targets ahead of the platform return a Doppler upshifted signal (slightly higher in frequency) and targets behind the platform return a Doppler downshifted signal (slightly lower in frequency).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] The amount of shift varies with the angle forward or backward from the ortho-normal direction.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] By knowing the speed of the platform, target signal return is placed in a specific angle "bin" that changes over time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Signals are integrated over time and thus the radar "beam" is synthetically reduced to a much smaller aperture – or more accurately (and based on the ability to distinguish smaller Doppler shifts) the system can have hundreds of very "tight" beams concurrently.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This technique dramatically improves angular resolution; however, it is far more difficult to take advantage of this technique for range resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A common technique for many radar systems (usually also found in SAR systems) is to "chirp" the signal.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] In a "chirped" radar, the pulse is allowed to be much longer.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] A longer pulse allows more energy to be emitted, and hence received, but usually hinders range resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] But in a chirped radar, this longer pulse also has a frequency shift during the pulse (hence the chirp or frequency shift).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] When the "chirped" signal is returned, it must be correlated with the sent pulse.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Classically, in analog systems, it is passed to a dispersive delay line (often a surface acoustic wave device) that has the property of varying velocity of propagation based on frequency.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] This technique "compresses" the pulse in time – thus having the effect of a much shorter pulse (improved range resolution) while having the benefit of longer pulse length (much more signal energy returned).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p01] Newer systems use digital pulse correlation to find the pulse return in the signal.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In a typical SAR application, a single radar antenna is attached to an aircraft or spacecraft such that a substantial component of the antenna's radiated beam has a wave-propagation direction perpendicular to the flight-path direction.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The beam is allowed to be broad in the vertical direction so it will illuminate the terrain from nearly beneath the aircraft out toward the horizon.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The differing times at which echoes return allow points at different distances to be distinguished.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Image resolution of SAR in its range coordinate (expressed in image pixels per distance unit) is mainly proportional to the radio bandwidth of whatever type of pulse is used.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In the cross-range coordinate, the similar resolution is mainly proportional to the bandwidth of the Doppler shift of the signal returns within the beamwidth.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Since Doppler frequency depends on the angle of the scattering point's direction from the broadside direction, the Doppler bandwidth available within the beamwidth is the same at all ranges.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Hence the theoretical spatial resolution limits in both image dimensions remain constant with variation of range.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] However, in practice, both the errors that accumulate with data-collection time and the particular techniques used in post-processing further limit cross-range resolution at long ranges.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The total signal is that from a beamwidth-sized patch of the ground.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] To produce a beam that is narrow in the cross-range direction, diffraction effects require that the antenna be wide in that dimension.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The process can be thought of as combining the series of spatially distributed observations as if all had been made simultaneously with an antenna as long as the beamwidth and focused on that particular point.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The "synthetic aperture" simulated at maximum system range by this process not only is longer than the real antenna, but, in practical applications, it is much longer than the radar aircraft, and tremendously longer than the radar spacecraft.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Although some references to SARs have characterized them as "radar telescopes", their actual optical analogy is the microscope, the detail in their images being smaller than the length of the synthetic aperture.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In radar-engineering terms, while the target area is in the "far field" of the illuminating antenna, it is in the "near field" of the simulated one.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Careful design and operation can accomplish resolution of items smaller than a millionth of the range, for example, 30 centimetres (12 in) at 300 kilometres (190 mi).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The conversion of return delay time to geometric range can be very accurate because of the natural constancy of the speed and direction of propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] SAR's in spacecraft avoid that atmosphere problem, but still must make corrections for known antenna movements due to rotations of the spacecraft, even those that are reactions to movements of onboard machinery.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Locating a SAR in a crewed space vehicle may require that the humans carefully remain motionless relative to the vehicle during data collection periods.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Returns from scatterers within the range extent of any image are spread over a matching time interval.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The inter-pulse period must be long enough to allow farthest-range returns from any pulse to finish arriving before the nearest-range ones from the next pulse begin to appear, so that those do not overlap each other in time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] On the other hand, the interpulse rate must be fast enough to provide sufficient samples for the desired across-range (or across-beam) resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] When the radar is to be carried by a high-speed vehicle and is to image a large area at fine resolution, those conditions may clash, leading to what has been called SAR's ambiguity problem.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The same considerations apply to "conventional" radars also, but this problem occurs significantly only when resolution is so fine as to be available only through SAR processes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Since the basis of the problem is the information-carrying capacity of the single signal-input channel provided by one antenna, the only solution is to use additional channels fed by additional antennas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The system then becomes a hybrid of a SAR and a phased array, sometimes being called a Vernier array.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Combining the series of observations requires significant computational resources, usually using Fourier transform techniques.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The high digital computing speed now available allows such processing to be done in near-real time on board a SAR aircraft.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] (There is necessarily a minimum time delay until all parts of the signal have been received.) The result is a map of radar reflectivity, including both amplitude and phase.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The amplitude information, when shown in a map-like display, gives information about ground cover in much the same way that a black-and-white photo does.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Variations in processing may also be done in either vehicle-borne stations or ground stations for various purposes, so as to accentuate certain image features for detailed target-area analysis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Although the phase information in an image is generally not made available to a human observer of an image display device, it can be preserved numerically, and sometimes allows certain additional features of targets to be recognized.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] This effect is the same as is apparent both visually and photographically in laser-illuminated optical scenes.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The scale of that random speckle structure is governed by the size of the synthetic aperture in wavelengths, and cannot be finer than the system's resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Speckle structure can be subdued at the expense of resolution.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Before rapid digital computers were available, the data processing was done using an optical holography technique.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The analog radar data were recorded as a holographic interference pattern on photographic film at a scale permitting the film to preserve the signal bandwidths (for example, 1:1,000,000 for a radar using a 0.6-meter wavelength).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Then light using, for example, 0.6-micrometer waves (as from a helium–neon laser) passing through the hologram could project a terrain image at a scale recordable on another film at reasonable processor focal distances of around a meter.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] This worked because both SAR and phased arrays are fundamentally similar to optical holography, but using microwaves instead of light waves.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The "optical data-processors" developed for this radar purpose were the first effective analog optical computer systems, and were, in fact, devised before the holographic technique was fully adapted to optical imaging.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Because of the different sources of range and across-range signal structures in the radar signals, optical data-processors for SAR included not only both spherical and cylindrical lenses, but sometimes conical ones.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The following considerations apply also to real-aperture terrain-imaging radars, but are more consequential when resolution in range is matched to a cross-beam resolution that is available only from a SAR.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The two dimensions of a radar image are range and cross-range.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Radar images of limited patches of terrain can resemble oblique photographs, but not ones taken from the location of the radar.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] This is because the range coordinate in a radar image is perpendicular to the vertical-angle coordinate of an oblique photo.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Because slant ranges to level terrain vary in vertical angle, each elevation of such terrain appears as a curved surface, specifically a hyperbolic cosine one.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Verticals at various ranges are perpendiculars to those curves.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The viewer's apparent looking directions are parallel to the curve's "hypcos" axis.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Items directly beneath the radar appear as if optically viewed horizontally (i.e., from the side) and those at far ranges as if optically viewed from directly above.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] These curvatures are not evident unless large extents of near-range terrain, including steep slant ranges, are being viewed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] When viewed as specified above, fine-resolution radar images of small areas can appear most nearly like familiar optical ones, for two reasons.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The first reason is easily understood by imagining a flagpole in the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The slant-range to its upper end is less than that to its base.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Therefore, the pole can appear correctly top-end up only when viewed in the above orientation.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Secondly, the radar illumination then being downward, shadows are seen in their most-familiar "overhead-lighting" direction.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The image of the pole's top will overlay that of some terrain point which is on the same slant range arc but at a shorter horizontal range ("ground-range").
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Images of scene surfaces which faced both the illumination and the apparent eyepoint will have geometries that resemble those of an optical scene viewed from that eyepoint.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] However, slopes facing the radar will be foreshortened and ones facing away from it will be lengthened from their horizontal (map) dimensions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The former will therefore be brightened and the latter dimmed.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Returns from slopes steeper than perpendicular to slant range will be overlaid on those of lower-elevation terrain at a nearer ground-range, both being visible but intermingled.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] This is especially the case for vertical surfaces like the walls of buildings.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Another viewing inconvenience that arises when a surface is steeper than perpendicular to the slant range is that it is then illuminated on one face but "viewed" from the reverse face.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Some return from the roof may overlay that from the front wall, and both of those may overlay return from terrain in front of the building.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The visible building shadow will include those of all illuminated items.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Long shadows may exhibit blurred edges due to the illuminating antenna's movement during the "time exposure" needed to create the image.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Surfaces that we usually consider rough will, if that roughness consists of relief less than the radar wavelength, behave as smooth mirrors, showing, beyond such a surface, additional images of items in front of it.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Those mirror images will appear within the shadow of the mirroring surface, sometimes filling the entire shadow, thus preventing recognition of the shadow.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The direction of overlay of any scene point is not directly toward the radar, but toward that point of the SAR's current path direction that is nearest to the target point.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] If the SAR is "squinting" forward or aft away from the exactly broadside direction, then the illumination direction, and hence the shadow direction, will not be opposite to the overlay direction, but slanted to right or left from it.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] An image will appear with the correct projection geometry when viewed so that the overlay direction is vertical, the SAR's flight-path is above the image, and range increases somewhat downward.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Objects in motion within a SAR scene alter the Doppler frequencies of the returns.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Such objects therefore appear in the image at locations offset in the across-range direction by amounts proportional to the range-direction component of their velocity.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Road vehicles may be depicted off the roadway and therefore not recognized as road traffic items.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Trains appearing away from their tracks are more easily properly recognized by their length parallel to known trackage as well as by the absence of an equal length of railbed signature and of some adjacent terrain, both having been shadowed by the train.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] While images of moving vessels can be offset from the line of the earlier parts of their wakes, the more recent parts of the wake, which still partake of some of the vessel's motion, appear as curves connecting the vessel image to the relatively quiescent far-aft wake.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In such identifiable cases, speed and direction of the moving items can be determined from the amounts of their offsets.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The along-track component of a target's motion causes some defocus.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Random motions such as that of wind-driven tree foliage, vehicles driven over rough terrain, or humans or other animals walking or running generally render those items not focusable, resulting in blurring or even effective invisibility.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] These considerations, along with the speckle structure due to coherence, take some getting used to in order to correctly interpret SAR images.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] To assist in that, large collections of significant target signatures have been accumulated by performing many test flights over known terrains and cultural objects.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In recent years, the commercialization of synthetic aperture radar (SAR) technology has expanded, with private companies launching SAR satellites to provide high-resolution imaging capabilities for various applications.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] These include environmental monitoring, disaster response, defense and intelligence, infrastructure monitoring, and maritime surveillance.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Capella Space, an American Earth observation company, operates a constellation of SAR satellites designed to provide all-weather, high-resolution imagery.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Capella was the first U.S. company to deploy a commercial SAR satellite and continues to expand its fleet with advanced SAR capabilities, including higher resolution, faster revisit times, and automated tasking.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] SAR data is often used by government agencies, defense organizations, and commercial customers to monitor changes on Earth in near real-time.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Other commercial SAR providers include ICEYE, a Finnish company specializing in small SAR satellites, and Airbus, which operates the TerraSAR-X and PAZ missions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The commercial SAR industry has grown significantly as advancements in satellite miniaturization, cloud-based data processing, and artificial intelligence enhance accessibility and utility for a broad range of users.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The history of synthetic-aperture radar begins in 1951, with the invention of the technology by mathematician Carl A.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Wiley, and its development in the following decade.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Initially developed for military use, the technology has since been applied in the field of planetary science.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] A technique closely related to SAR uses an array (referred to as a "phased array") of real antenna elements spatially distributed over either one or two dimensions perpendicular to the radar-range dimension.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] These physical arrays are truly synthetic ones, indeed being created by synthesis of a collection of subsidiary physical antennas.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Their operation need not involve motion relative to targets.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] All elements of these arrays receive simultaneously in real time, and the signals passing through them can be individually subjected to controlled shifts of the phases of those signals.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] One result can be to respond most strongly to radiation received from a specific small scene area, focusing on that area to determine its contribution to the total signal received.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The coherently detected set of signals received over the entire array aperture can be replicated in several data-processing channels and processed differently in each.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The set of responses thus traced to different small scene areas can be displayed together as an image of the scene.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In comparison, a SAR's (commonly) single physical antenna element gathers signals at different positions at different times.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] When the radar is carried by an aircraft or an orbiting vehicle, those positions are functions of a single variable, distance along the vehicle's path, which is a single mathematical dimension (not necessarily the same as a linear geometric dimension).
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The signals are stored, thus becoming functions, no longer of time, but of recording locations along that dimension.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] When the stored signals are read out later and combined with specific phase shifts, the result is the same as if the recorded data had been gathered by an equally long and shaped phased array.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] What is thus synthesized is a set of signals equivalent to what could have been received simultaneously by such an actual large-aperture (in one dimension) phased array.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The SAR simulates (rather than synthesizes) that long one-dimensional phased array.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Although the term in the title of this article has thus been incorrectly derived, it is now firmly established by half a century of usage.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Temporal frequencies being the variables commonly used by radar engineers, their analyses of SAR systems are usually (and very productively) couched in such terms.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] In particular, the variation of phase during flight over the length of the synthetic aperture is seen as a sequence of Doppler shifts of the received frequency from that of the transmitted frequency.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Once the received data have been recorded and thus have become timeless, the SAR data-processing situation is also understandable as a special type of phased array, treatable as a completely geometric process.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] The core of both the SAR and the phased array techniques is that the distances that radar waves travel to and back from each scene element consist of some integer number of wavelengths plus some fraction of a "final" wavelength.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Those fractions cause differences between the phases of the re-radiation received at various SAR or array positions.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] Coherent detection is needed to capture the signal phase information in addition to the signal amplitude information.
[src:remote-sensing-analysis/synthetic-aperture-radar-p02] That type of detection requires finding the differences between the phases of the received signals and the simultaneous phase of a well-preserved sample of the transmitted illumination.
